    <span></span><span></span><span></span>
  </button>
</nav>

<div style="background:var(--white);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border)">
  <div class="hero">
    <span class="hero-tag">Peer-reviewed research</span>
    <h1>Snow Water Equivalent &amp; <em>Temperature Dynamics</em> in Colorado Counties</h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">A longitudinal analysis of annual SWE trends across San Juan, Gunnison, and Summit counties from 1980 to 2025, using PRISM gridded climate data and SNOTEL station records.</p>
    <div class="hero-meta">
      <span><span class="dot"></span>1980 – 2025</span>
      <span><span class="dot"></span>88 weather stations</span>
      <span><span class="dot"></span>3 counties</span>
      <span><span class="dot"></span>PRISM &amp; SNOTEL data</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <p class="section-label">At a glance</p>
  <h2>Study overview</h2>
  <p>This study investigates the relationship between annual average temperature and snow water equivalent across three high-elevation Colorado counties. Using spatially-averaged SNOTEL station data and PRISM-derived temperature rasters, we quantify the strength of temperature–SWE correlations and model long-term trends through linear regression.</p>
  <div class="stats-grid">
    <div class="stat-card"><div class="stat-val">46</div><div class="stat-label">Years of data<br>1980 – 2025</div></div>
    <div class="stat-card"><div class="stat-val">88</div><div class="stat-label">SNOTEL stations<br>across Colorado</div></div>
    <div class="stat-card"><div class="stat-val">3</div><div class="stat-label">Counties analyzed<br>San Juan, Gunnison, Summit</div></div>
    <div class="stat-card"><div class="stat-val">4km</div><div class="stat-label">PRISM grid resolution<br>temperature rasters</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<hr class="divider">

<div class="section">
  <p class="section-label">Key findings</p>
  <h2>Correlation results</h2>
  <p>All three counties exhibit a statistically significant negative correlation between annual average temperature and snow water equivalent, consistent with expectations for high-elevation snowpack dynamics.</p>
  <div class="findings-grid">
    <div class="finding-card sj">
      <div class="finding-county">San Juan County</div>
      <div class="finding-r">r = −0.566</div>
      <div class="finding-desc">Moderate-strong negative correlation. Strongest temperature–SWE relationship of the three counties studied.</div>
      <div class="finding-p">p &lt; 0.001 &nbsp;·&nbsp; n = 46</div>
    </div>
    <div class="finding-card gu">
      <div class="finding-county">Gunnison County</div>
      <div class="finding-r">r = −0.413</div>
      <div class="finding-desc">Moderate negative correlation. Statistically significant relationship between warming trends and snowpack decline.</div>
      <div class="finding-p">p = 0.004 &nbsp;·&nbsp; n = 46</div>
    </div>
    <div class="finding-card su">
      <div class="finding-county">Summit County</div>
      <div class="finding-r">r = −0.317</div>
      <div class="finding-desc">Weak-moderate negative correlation. Significant at the 95% confidence level, approaching threshold.</div>
      <div class="finding-p">p = 0.032 &nbsp;·&nbsp; n = 46</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<hr class="divider">

<div class="section">
  <p class="section-label">Visualizations</p>
  <h2>Linear regression plots</h2>
  <p>Scatter plots with fitted regression lines and y = mx + b equations for each county will be embedded here. Charts are generated from Python (matplotlib) and rendered interactively.</p>
  <div class="chart-placeholder">
    <svg width="48" height="48" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><rect x="3" y="3" width="18" height="18" rx="2"/><path d="M7 17l3-4 3 3 3-5"/></svg>
    <p>Regression plots will be embedded here</p>
  </div>
</div>

<hr class="divider">

<div class="section">
  <p class="section-label">Methodology</p>
  <h2>Data &amp; methods</h2>
  <div class="methods-list">
    <li><span class="method-num">1</span><span><strong style="color:var(--text);font-weight:500">SWE data</strong> — Annual SWE averages computed from NRCS SNOTEL stations within each county boundary. Station values averaged to produce a single county-level SWE estimate per year.</span></li>
    <li><span class="method-num">2</span><span><strong style="color:var(--text);font-weight:500">Temperature data</strong> — Annual average temperatures derived from PRISM 4km gridded rasters, clipped to county boundaries in GIS. Zonal statistics (mean) extracted per year.</span></li>
    <li><span class="method-num">3</span><span><strong style="color:var(--text);font-weight:500">Statistical analysis</strong> — Pearson correlation coefficients computed between annual temperature and SWE for each county. Linear regression models fitted and visualized using Python (scipy, matplotlib).</span></li>
    <li><span class="method-num">4</span><span><strong style="color:var(--text);font-weight:500">Significance testing</strong> — Two-tailed p-values reported for each correlation. Significance threshold set at α = 0.05.</span></li>
  </div>
</div>

